@GRMIDX{{index="Use of the @HI{{Zu}} Form" grammar="Use of the @HI{{Zu}} Form"}}

<body>

<h1>Use of the @HI{{Zu}} Form</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @FORMATION{{@HI{{@EM{{@Vnaistem{{}}zu}}[ni]}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
The @HI{{Zu}} form is an older form of the negative conjugation of a verb.
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="without">The @HI{{zu}}</a> form can be used in place of <a href="grammar-nai-de.html">@HI{{ndaide}}</a> to mean "without" in the sense of attendant circumstances.
This usage is used more in written work than in speech.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{hurry}}:iso}}ideitanode,kagiwokake@EM{{zuni}},@FG{{@KJ{{exit}}:de}}kaketeshimatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I was in such a hurry that I left without ocking up.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="without-means">The @HI{{zu}}</a> form can be used in place of <a href="grammar-nai-de.html">@HI{{ndaide}}</a> to mean "without" in the sense of a lack of means.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{resign^write}}:jisho}}wo@FG{{@KJ{{use}}:tsuka}}wa@EM{{zuni}}@FG{{@KJ{{new^hear}}:shinbun'}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{read}}:yo}}meruyouninaritai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'd like to be able to read the newspaper without using a dictionary.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="reason-cause">The @HI{{zu}}</a> form can be used in place of <a href="grammar-nakute.html">@HI{{nakute}}</a> to indicate a reason or a cause.
In this usage, the particle @HI{{ni}} does not appear.
This usage is used more in written work than in speech.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{child}}domono@FG{{@KJ{{heat}}:netsu}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{below}}:sa}}garazu,@FG{{@KJ{{heart^distribute}}:shinpai}}shimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The child's temperature diudn't come down so I was worried.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="juxtapose">The @HI{{zu}}</a> form can be used to juxtapose clauses where the first is denied and replaced by the second.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{rice*field^in}}:tanaka}}sanha@KJ{{now^month}}@FG{{@KJ{{exit^lengthen}}:shucchou}}@EM{{sezu}},@KJ{{come^month}}@KJ{{exit^lengthen}}surukotoninarimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Tanaka isn't going away on business this month; he is to go next month instead.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
An archaic negative form of verbs, <a href="grammar-nu-archaic-negative.html">@HI{{nu}}</a>, also exists. The differences are that @HI{{zuni}} can be used as a continuative,
and @HI{{nu}} can be used at the end of a sentence or before a noun, auxiliary or conjunction.
</p>

